  footnotes: []
english:
  title: To Suh Gangjoong
  author: Yun Ja-young
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Banished here, my hair has turned entirely white.
    I drive my horse through the countryside, wandering where the path leads.
    These idle cloud-wrapped mountains are fit to hide my traces,
    and in the lingering years, I simply fill my days with writing.

    I know well that an old tree cannot spring back to life—
    so do not speak of kindling dead ashes into flame twice over.
    But should you later hold office in the southern court,
    I ask that you might visit the riverside, and seek me out.
  footnotes:
    - The poem references Qu Yuan (三閭大夫), the great minister of ancient Chu who was exiled and died by the Miluo River, creating a literary parallel between the poet's exile and that of this classical figure.
    - The image of 'dead ashes' and 'kindling flame twice' suggests the impossibility of restoring former glory or position, yet the final stanza holds onto a fragile hope of friendship's remembrance.
